english:
  title: Stupa Inscription for Venerable Bojet, Posthumously Titled Seonggak
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the twentieth year of King Gongmin's reign, on the tenth day of the ninth month of the year Gyeongseul, the Master was summoned to the capital. On the sixteenth day, at the Gwangmyeong Temple where the Master was residing, a great assembly was held of monks from the two schools and five teachings of all the mountains. Their self-attained understanding was tested in what was called the "Examination of Practice." The king himself attended to observe. After the Master burned incense and ascended the dharma seat, he spoke thus:

    "Cast off the ruts of ancient and modern times. Sweep away all traces of the common and the sage. Cut through the life-root of every monk. Shake free the nets of doubt that bind all beings. Control and command rest in the palm of the hand. Transformation and adaptability turn on the hinge. The Buddhas of three worlds and the patriarchs of all ages—their principle is one. All virtuous ones here assembled, I ask you to answer with truth."

    Then one by one they came forward. With bowed backs and sweating foreheads, all said they had not understood. Some penetrated principle but were obstructed by phenomena. Others, wild in their exuberance, stumbled in their words. With a single phrase they were dismissed. The king seemed displeased. Later came Master Hwanan Suyeon. The Master questioned him three times, and when the examination of the three gates concluded, he returned to Hoegam Temple.

    On the twenty-sixth day of the eighth month of the year Sinhai, the king sent the Minister of Public Works, Zhang Ziwen, bearing an imperial edict with seal, dharma robes, and begging bowl. The Master was invested as the Royal Teacher, Great Patriarch of the Jogye School, Supreme Overseer of all Schools, and given the title Venerable Bojet—"One who Diligently Cultivates Original Wisdom, Revives the Patriarchal Way, Blesses the Nation and Protects the World." Songwang Temple was declared the foremost dharma place in our land, and the Master was commanded to reside there.

    In the autumn of the year Imja, the Master recalled the records of the three mountains and rain water left by his master Jigong, wishing to move to Hoegam Temple. At that very moment he was summoned to preside over a dharma assembly at this temple, and obtaining permission, took up residence here. The Master said: "My late master Jigong had once planned the reconstruction of these halls, but they were destroyed in warfare. How could I dare not carry forward his intention?" He consulted with the assembly, and the buildings were expanded and enlarged. When the work was completed, in the fourth month of the year Byungsin, a grand consecration ceremony was held.

    The court officials remarked that Hoegam Temple lay so close to the capital that scholars and women came and went day and night in endless streams, sometimes abandoning their occupations. It would be best to restrict this. So an edict came directing the Master to move to Yeongewon Temple. Pressed by this command, the Master fell ill. He was placed in a palanquin and carried out through the three gates toward the pond. There he guided the bearers to take the path through the Gate of Nirvana. The assembly was bewildered and wept with breaking voices. The Master looked back and said: "Strive, strive! Do not abandon your practice on my account. My journey shall end in Yeohheung."

    When they reached the Han River, the Master told his escort officer Dak Jeom: "My illness has grown grave. I beg you, let us travel by boat." They poled upstream for seven days before reaching Yeohheung. The Master told Dak: "I wish to rest a while until my condition improves." Dak reluctantly agreed. They lodged at Shinneung Temple. On the fifteenth day of the fifth month, Dak urged him to depart at once. The Master said: "This is no difficulty. My departure comes now." That same day at the hour of Chen, he passed away in peace.

    The people of the region saw five-colored clouds covering the mountain peaks. After the cremation, though there were no clouds above, rain fell within several hundred paces around. One hundred fifty-five relics were recovered. Through prayers, these multiplied to five hundred fifty-eight. How many more the four assemblies of disciples found in the ashes and kept secret, none could say. Divine light illuminated the earth for three days and then ceased. The monk Dar-yeo dreamed of a dragon coiled beneath the cremation platform, taking the form of a horse. When the remains were transported back to Hoegam Temple by boat, no rain fell, yet the waters ran high—all said it was the dragon's help. On the fifteenth day of the eighth month, a stupa was erected on the northern cliff of the temple. The bone relics from the crown were enshrined at Shinneung Temple, marking where the Master passed away, and covered with a stone bell to prevent any corruption of the record.

    Word of these events reached the throne. The Master was given the posthumous title Seonggak. The king commanded me, Saek, to compose this inscription, and commanded Yi Jung-hwa to write it in seal script on the plaque.

    I have carefully examined the record: The Master's name was Hyegeun, his dharma name Naeong. He was originally called Wonhye. He lived fifty-seven years and had thirty-eight years in the monastic life. He was from Yeongae Prefecture. His family name was A. His father, whose name was Seo, served as Director of the Royal Provisions. His mother was Lady Jung, from Yeongsan County. Lady Jung dreamed that a golden hawk flew down and pecked her head, suddenly dropping an egg brilliant with five colors that fell into her bosom. She became pregnant and gave birth to the Master on the fifteenth day of the first month in the year Gyeongsin of the Yeonwu era.

    When he barely reached manhood, a neighbor's friend died. He asked the elders: "Where do the dead go?" They all said they did not know. His heart grieved deeply. He fled to Gongdeok Mountain, took refuge with Master Yoryeon, and received ordination. Master Yoryeon asked: "For what purpose have you left home?" The young monk replied: "To transcend the three realms and bring benefit to all beings." He requested teaching. The master asked: "What is this thing that comes here?" The monk answered: "That which can speak and hear, that which can come." "But I do not know the method of practice." The master said: "Nor do I know. Go and seek. There will be another teacher."

    In the year Gapsin of the Jijung era, he came to Hoegam Temple. Day and night he sat in solitude until suddenly he awakened to the way. His resolve to seek a master in China became firm. In the third month of the year Muza, he arrived in Yanjing and paid reverence to Jigong. His questions and answers harmonized perfectly. In the first month of the year Gyeonggin, the tenth year of Jijung, when Jigong assembled his disciples and posed a question, none could answer. The Master stepped forward and spoke a few phrases, bowed three times, and withdrew. Jigong was the one hundred eighth patriarch from the Western Buddha lands.

    That spring he traveled south through Jiangsu and Zhejiang. In the eighth month of autumn, he paid reverence to Master Pyeongsan. Pyeongsan asked: "Whom have you seen?" The Master replied: "Master Jigong of the Western lands, who wields a thousand swords daily." Pyeongsan said: "Set aside Jigong's thousand swords. Bring me your one sword." The Master seized Pyeongsan with his meditation mat and threw him onto the meditation bench. Pyeongsan cried out: "The thief is killing me!" The Master said: "I am the sword. I can kill and I can give life." He then lifted Pyeongsan up. Pyeongsan presented him with the robes and whisk that had been transmitted through Seolam as tokens of transmission.

    In the spring of Sinmyo year, he reached Mount Putuo and paid homage to Avalokiteshvara. In Imjin year, he came to Fenglong Mountain to pay reverence to Master Cheonam. At that time, a thousand monks were assembled for the selection of those to enter his chamber. When asked whence he came, the Master replied. Cheonam asked: "Before your parents were born, from where did you come?" The Master answered: "This morning is the second day of the fourth month." Cheonam approved him. That year he returned north and again paid reverence to Jigong, who gave him the dharma robes, whisk, and Sanskrit texts. From then on he wandered through the mountains and rivers of the Yan and Dai regions, a solitary free wanderer whose fame spread within the palace.

    In the autumn of Eulmi year, following a sacred edict, he took residence at Gwangje Temple in the capital. On the fifteenth day of the tenth month in Byungsin year, he held an opening ceremony. The emperor sent the Commissioner Yaxientiemuer bearing a golden brocade robe and gifts, while the Crown Prince sent a golden brocade robe and an ivory whisk. When the Master received the robe, he asked the assembly: "Serene emptiness, the original void with not a single thing—from whence comes this radiance?" No one could answer. He said slowly: "From within the golden mouth in the nine-layered palace." He then burned incense to bless the imperial life, ascended the seat, held the staff across his lap, spoke a few phrases, and descended.

    In the spring of Musulyear, he took leave of Jigong, received the seal of transmission, and returned east. As he traveled, he stopped and started, teaching according to each person's capacity. In Gyeongja year, he entered Mount Tae. In Sinchuk year winter, the king sent the Imperial Advisor Bang Jeol to bring him to the capital and requested that he expound the essentials of mind. The king bestowed upon him a fully embroidered robe and a crystal whisk. The princess offered a carnelian whisk. The empress herself made an offering and requested he reside at Sinkwang Temple. The Master declined. The king said: "Then in the dharma, I too must withdraw." Reluctantly, the Master went to Sinkwang Temple.

    In the eleventh month, the Red Bandits ravaged the region and the whole nation fled south. The monks, terrified, begged to escape. The Master said: "We need only preserve the dharma. What can the bandits do?" Within days their pleas grew urgent. That night the Master dreamed of a divine being with a dark mark upon his face, bowing in full regalia, who said: "If everyone scatters, the bandits will surely destroy the temple. I beg you, master, hold firm to your resolve." The next day when the Master visited the earth god's shrine, he saw the very face from his dream. Indeed, the bandits did not come.

    In Gyemyo year, he entered Mount Guweol. The palace sent the eunuch Kim Jung-sun to request his return. In the third month of Eulsa year, he went to the palace to petition for retirement and finally obtained his long-cherished wish. He wandered through Mount Yongmun, Wonjeok, and other temples. In Byungoh year, he entered Mount Geumgang. In Jeongmi year autumn, he resided at Cheonpyeong Temple. That winter, the venerable one at Yebaoam brought Master Jigong's robe and handwritten letter, presenting them to the Master and saying: "These are Master Jigong's final instructions." In Giyou year, he entered Mount Tae again. In the spring of Gyeongseul year, the official Dal-ye brought Master Jigong's remains and enshrined them at Hoegam Temple. The Master paid reverence to his teacher's relics, and then went to preside over the dharma assembly at Gwangmyeong Temple for the summer retreat. When autumn began, he returned to Hoegam Temple. The ninth month was the time of the Examination of Practice.

    The Master's dwelling was called the Rivermoon Pavilion. Though he never studied worldly letters in his lifetime, whenever asked to compose verses, he would take brush in hand and write as though thought had never touched the matter—yet his words reached into profound depths of principle and meaning. In his later years, he loved ink painting, and his landscape paintings approached both the orthodox and expedient ways. Alas, when the way is realized, how naturally all abilities flow forth!

    I humbly bow my head and compose this inscription:

    *Rare as the horn of the unicorn,*
    *Stands the Awakened One called Seonggak,*
    *Master to kings,*
    *Eyes of gods and men.*

    *All monks took him as patriarch,*
    *Gathering like water to a gorge,*
    *Yet few truly understood*
    *The lofty monument he raised.*

    *His birth gleamed bright,*
    *The hawk's dream was luminous,*
    *Dragons guarded the rites,*
    *And his end proved beautiful.*

    *The relics showed forth*
    *Extraordinary grace—*
    *Wide as the river flows,*
    *Clear as the bright moon shines.*

    *Is it emptiness? Is it form?*
    *Above and below lie open.*
    *His sublime character,*
    *Shall never fade from history.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three worlds' refers to the realms of desire, form, and formlessness in Buddhist cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'dharma seat' (법좌) is the elevated platform from which a master teaches, symbolizing authority in the transmission of Buddhist teaching.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'functional examination' (공부선) was a formal testing of monks' realization conducted before the royal court.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Eyes of gods and men'' (인천의 안목) is a traditional phrase denoting supreme wisdom and spiritual discernment.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Gate of Nirvana' through which the Master departed symbolically represents his passing into ultimate liberation.
  - key: ''
    value: The appearance of relics (sarira) following cremation was traditionally understood as a sign of exceptional spiritual attainment.
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Putuo (Potalaka) is the mythological abode of Avalokiteshvara in Buddhist tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'golden mouth in the nine-layered palace' refers poetically to the imperial throne and its authority.
